[[Image:Malhargad pinnacle.jpg|thumb|250px|Detail on temple roof, Malhargad]]

'''Malhargad''' is a hill fort in western India near [[Saswad]], {{convert|30|km|mi}} from [[Pune]]. It is also known as '''Sonori Fort''' due to the village of [[Sonori]] being situated at its base. The fort was named for the god [[Khandoba|Malhari]] and was the last fort built by the [[Marathas]], about 1775.<ref name="Burgess">{{cite book|last=Burgess|first=James|title=Lists of the Antiquarian Remains in the Bombay Presidency|publisher=Govt. Central Press|date=1885|page=82}}</ref>

The Sahyadri range to the west of Pune in Velha taluka is split, and the forts Rajgad and Torna are on one branch while Forts [[Sinhagad]], [[Purandar]], [[Vajragad]] and '''Malhargad''' on the other. This range is known as the [[Bhuleshwar range]] which is spread along the East-West direction.  The fort is believed to be built to keep watch on [[Dive ghat]] along the Pune-Saswad route. The fort was built during the period of 1757 to 1760. The fort was built by BhivrÃ¢o Yashvant and Krishnaji MÃ¢dhavrÃ¢o PÃ¢nsÃª, a Peshwa Sardar,<ref name="Burgess" /> who was the chief in charge of Tofkhana of the Peshwas. Citations of a visit of Elder Madhavrao Peshwe to the fort are available in historic documents. A palace, belonging to Panse, can be seen in the Sonori village though much of it is in ruins. 

The fort is in good condition. There are two temples constructed side-by-side: the smaller for Lord [[Khandoba]], and the larger for Lord [[Shiva|Mahadeva]]. From the top of this fort, the city of [[Jejuri]] and [[Parvati Temple|Parvati hills]] can be seen. The forts of [[Sinhagad]], [[Purandar fort|Purandar]], and [[Vajragad]] are also visible.{{Fact|date=November 2008}} 

